    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_285110965" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/285110965" />
    <a title="Regan Walker" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7363897-regan-walker"><img alt="Regan Walker" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442636914p2/7363897.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/285110965?book_show_action=true">Feb 27, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Regan Walker" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Regan Walker" href="/user/show/7363897-regan-walker">Regan Walker</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer285110965" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14981173818048120122">The first thing you need to know about this time travel romance is that the majority of it takes place in 1988. I didn&apos;t know that when I bought it. But the 5 star ratings convinced me to buy it. After reading the first 25 pages, I was back on Amazon looking at the reviews to see if I&apos;d missed something. I did. The low ratings tell a different story: an annoying heroine, contrived plot developments, no happy ending, etc. How, I asked myself, could all those 5 star raters be so wrong? So, I decid</span>
  <span id="freeText14981173818048120122" style="display:none">The first thing you need to know about this time travel romance is that the majority of it takes place in 1988. I didn't know that when I bought it. But the 5 star ratings convinced me to buy it. After reading the first 25 pages, I was back on Amazon looking at the reviews to see if I'd missed something. I did. The low ratings tell a different story: an annoying heroine, contrived plot developments, no happy ending, etc. How, I asked myself, could all those 5 star raters be so wrong? So, I decided to be fair and give the book another chance and make my review a project of sorts...to give the readers the real scoop. Here it is.<br /><br />The author in an end note (written 14 years after the book) says this book is about alcoholism without anyone in it being an alcoholic. I never saw it, of course, but she says it's about an alcoholic personality--a "dry drunk"--one who looks for the most moral person they know and then tries to destroy that person. Once you understand this, the heroine (the moral one) becomes more understandable. Her beau at the beginning, Robert the surgeon, is the alcoholic personality.<br /><br />The beginning is slow, overly long and the heroine--named regrettably "Dougless"--will come across as annoying. She's the youngest sister in a family of accomplished women, and her love life has been one bad choice after another, including her current one. She is living with Robert, a surgeon, hoping for marriage. Robert has a spoiled daughter and a former wife he calls "cold." When Dougless, the boyfriend and his daughter go to England on vacation, it just gets worse. That was the author's first mistake: three annoying characters in the first few chapters. It didn't exactly draw me in. I can only assume the readers who persisted at that point are among Deveraux's fans. I was bored to death. Anyway, when the threesome blows up and the boyfriend and his daughter leave Dougless stranded in England, she goes into a church to cry on the grave of Nicholas Stafford, earl of Thornwyck, who died in 1564. Suddenly, the very same medieval man is standing before her, summoned by her crying.<br /><br />Deveraux spends too much time on Dougless' difficulty in accepting that Nicholas is from the long ago past--well over 100 pages. Much of the book is spent in the 20th century as Dougless and Nicholas deal with his acclimation to modern times and trying to figure out what happened to him that he would be wrongly accused of treason and sentenced to hang back in the 16th century. Along the way, and somewhat surprisingly, they fall in love and then Nicholas is yanked back into his own century. Of course, Dougless soon joins him and the roles are reversed.<br /><br />WHAT I LIKED:<br />--Nicholas' voice was medieval and he was convincing<br />--the heroine (at the end of the book)<br />--the dialog and writing were good; some of the one liners were priceless<br />--the historical details were accurate (if you ignore the fact the Moors were making glass mirrors in the 11th century, and later they were made in Vienna, so Nicholas, as a wealthy nobleman living in the 16th century, could have seen a glass mirror).<br />--the ending<br /><br />WHAT I DIDN'T LIKE:<br />--the heroine through much of the book (As some reviewers described her, she could be "weak," "a doormat" and "always crying." Besides, who would take what Robert the surgeon dished out and still claim to "love" him?)<br />--Inconsistencies in characters (Dougless was fine with Nicholas cutting her arm with his sword but cowered when he spoke to the coin dealer; when she wasn't sobbing, she actually, occasionally showed spunk. When, in the last third of the book, Dougless goes back to the 16th century, she actually develops a spine. I now see this as being possible because she is away from the alcoholic personality, Robert.)<br />--I felt like the author was trying to give me a history lesson through most of the book--a lecture on the differences between the 20th and 16th centuries. This occurred when they were shopping, in the hotel room, at the dentist's office, and whenever paper was discussed, and that doesn't even cover the parts that took place in the 16th century. It's not that I wasn't interested in some of this, but did she have to give us all her research? I suppose some readers of time travel delight in those long passages, but not me. I thought the historical comparisons made up too much of the story. This is supposed to be about a relationship.<br />--the ending (when you read it, you'll understand why I could both love and hate the ending)<br /><br />Having not read a lot of Deveraux, I cannot be counted among her fans, but I will say from the reviews of her books on Amazon, it appears she is a "hit or miss" author. Sometimes she tells a great tale, while other times she disappoints. That's not to say you shouldn't read her books, only that you should tread carefully in selecting. <br /><br />This one was rated as a 5 star by so many, you can't dismiss it. I found it difficult to rate given the issues I've mentioned, and it doesn't make my Best Medieval Romances list on Historical Romance Review. <br /><br />There are parts of the story that bored me, and I skipped those passages, but there were parts I loved and the ending is very bittersweet (I had tears running down my cheeks). So I can't dismiss this. It's quality romance, however it's not my cup of tea.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14981173818048120122" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


